WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.440
In this video, I will introduce the concepts of extended cost

2
00:00:04.440 --> 00:00:08.400
and full cost and how they affect supply chain decision-making.

3
00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:11.360
We will also learn how to calculate these metrics.

4
00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:11.360


5
00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:11.360


6
00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:18.040
Understanding different cost drivers in supply chain work is critical for making and communicating decisions.

7
00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:18.040


8
00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:18.040


9
00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:21.600
Unit cost refers to the cost of purchasing an additional unit and

10
00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:27.120
includes the manufacturer's raw material cost, production costs, and profit.

11
00:00:27.120 --> 00:00:32.560
For instance, in custom t-shirt manufacturing, the unit cost would cover raw material costs like blank

12
00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:40.440
t-shirts and ink, along with production costs such as energy and labor that increase as more t-shirts are produced.

13
00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:40.440


14
00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:40.440


15
00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:46.080
Extended cost represents the cost paid for the products only and does not include one-time expenses.

16
00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:46.080


17
00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:47.000


18
00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:50.840
Extended cost is the number of units purchased multiplied by the unit cost.

19
00:00:50.840 --> 00:00:50.840


20
00:00:50.840 --> 00:00:51.840


21
00:00:51.840 --> 00:00:56.560
Imagine you purchase ten custom shirts that cost $15 each.

22
00:00:56.560 --> 00:01:00.280
The extended cost is $150.

23
00:01:00.280 --> 00:01:00.280


24
00:01:00.280 --> 00:01:00.280


25
00:01:00.280 --> 00:01:05.600
Even when buying products from a supplier, there are often one-time costs that must be paid to enable production.

26
00:01:05.600 --> 00:01:05.600


27
00:01:05.600 --> 00:01:06.720


28
00:01:06.720 --> 00:01:10.000
Suppliers often pass these costs on to the purchasing company.

29
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:10.000


30
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:10.000


31
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:16.320
Common examples of non-recurring expenses include tooling or fixtures specific to the product being

32
00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:24.480
manufactured, engineering expenses to set up production, or even a minimum charge to occupy manufacturing equipment.

33
00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:24.480


34
00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:24.480


35
00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:28.640
As production volumes increase, it is common for non-recurring expenses to increase.

36
00:01:28.640 --> 00:01:35.360
This happens because higher volumes require either more manufacturing equipment or more labor for setup and management.

37
00:01:35.360 --> 00:01:35.360


38
00:01:35.360 --> 00:01:36.400


39
00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:41.760
Full cost represents the total amount a company must pay to buy a certain quantity of products.

40
00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:41.760


41
00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:41.760


42
00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:46.800
Full cost is the sum of the extended cost and the non-recurring expenses.

43
00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:46.800


44
00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:47.760


45
00:01:47.760 --> 00:01:51.000
When making a supply chain decision, focusing on the full cost is

46
00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:55.160
imperative because it is the total amount the company will pay to acquire the products.

47
00:01:55.160 --> 00:01:55.160


48
00:01:55.160 --> 00:01:55.160


49
00:01:55.160 --> 00:01:58.720
While this might seem like common sense, it is easy to be

50
00:01:58.720 --> 00:02:03.680
fooled by the allure of low non-recurring expenses or low unit costs.

51
00:02:03.680 --> 00:02:04.680


52
00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:04.680


53
00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:06.720
Let's revisit the custom t-shirt example.

54
00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:13.760
The shirts cost $15, but the supplier charges a $65 set-up fee regardless of the quantity purchased.

55
00:02:13.760 --> 00:02:20.480
This fee is a non-recurring expense to compensate the company for the time to load the artwork onto the printer.

56
00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:20.480


57
00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:20.480


58
00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:23.680
We can now calculate our full cost.

59
00:02:23.680 --> 00:02:32.000
We add our $150 extended cost from before to the $65 set-up fee, resulting in a full cost of $215.

60
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:32.000


61
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:32.000


62
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.360
Full cost often includes overhead rates.

63
00:02:35.360 --> 00:02:40.480
The overhead rate is a cost allocated to the production of a product or service.

64
00:02:40.480 --> 00:02:46.200
Overhead costs are expenses that are not directly tied to production such as the cost of the corporate office.

65
00:02:46.200 --> 00:02:46.200


66
00:02:46.200 --> 00:02:47.040


67
00:02:47.040 --> 00:02:50.240
Because overhead calculation methods vary from company to company,

68
00:02:50.240 --> 00:02:54.000
overhead rates are not included in the full cost calculations in this course.

69
00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:54.000


70
00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:54.000


71
00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:00.200
However, the principles you learn in this course will enable you to incorporate overhead rates into your reports.

72
00:03:00.200 --> 00:03:00.200


73
00:03:00.200 --> 00:03:01.200


74
00:03:01.200 --> 00:03:07.280
It is time to apply what you have learned about extended costs and full costs to our dataset.

